{"id":1863,"date":"2019-03-07T07:30:32","date_gmt":"2019-03-06T20:30:32","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/?p=1863"},"modified":"2023-09-07T14:33:06","modified_gmt":"2023-09-07T04:33:06","slug":"giving-and-receiving","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/giving-and-receiving\/","title":{"rendered":"Giving and Receiving in Japanese &#8211; Agemasu, Kuremasu, Moraimasu"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>The words used to describe the acts of giving and receiving in Japanese can be quite confusing, but they needn\u2019t be.<\/p>\n<p>In a nutshell, there are two words that mean \u201cto give\u201d:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>agemasu<\/li>\n<li>kuremasu<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>And another word that means \u201cto receive\u201d:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>moraimasu<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>What most often confuses people is the fact that there are three words to describe actions that, in English, can be expressed with just two words.<\/p>\n<p>More options = more trying-to-figure-out-when-to-use-what.<\/p>\n<p>Fortunately, however, there is a simple way to look at these words that will eliminate any uncertainty about their use in 99% of situations.<\/p>\n<p>In this article, we will see how we can easily differentiate between the words for \u201cgiving\u201d and \u201creceiving\u201d in Japanese. In doing so, we will also cover everything you need to know to form sentences using the verbs <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<!--more--><\/p>\n<div class=\"rw-toc\">\n<div class=\"rw-toc-title\">Table of Contents<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#give\"><strong>How to say &#8220;give&#8221; in Japanese<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\">\n<div><a href=\"#give-examples\">Example sentences using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#indirect-objects\">The non-existence of indirect objects<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#less-obvious-cases\">Determining which direction applies in less-obvious cases<\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#receive\"><strong>How to say &#8220;receive&#8221; in Japanese<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\">\n<div><a href=\"#moraimasu-particles\">Which particles to use with &#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#alt-approach-to-ni\">An alternative way to think about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span><\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#super-polite\"><strong>Bonus: Super-polite verbs for giving and receiving<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#takeaways\"><strong>Key Takeaways<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"example\"><\/div>\n<h2 id=\"give\">How to say \u201cgive\u201d in Japanese \u2013 Agemasu and Kuremasu<\/h2>\n<p>As we saw, Japanese has two words that mean \u201cto give\u201d &#8211; <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n<p>It is important to know that these words are NOT interchangeable.<\/p>\n<p>Only one is appropriate in any given situation. The best way to look at these words is to compare them to the words \u201cgo\u201d and \u201ccome\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>Why?<\/p>\n<p>Because \u201cgo\u201d and \u201ccome\u201d can both be used to describe the same action \u2013 all that is different is the <strong>perspective<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>Ultimately, both words describe the act of one person or thing moving from one place to another.<\/p>\n<p>We use the word \u201cgo\u201d when the direction of that movement is away from us, and we use the word \u201ccome\u201d when the direction of that movement is towards us.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1874\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/01-going-coming.png\" alt=\"Going vs Coming\" width=\"1060\" height=\"380\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/01-going-coming.png 1060w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/01-going-coming-300x108.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/01-going-coming-1024x367.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/01-going-coming-768x275.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1060px) 100vw, 1060px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The action itself is exactly the same \u2013 only the word used to describe it is different.<\/p>\n<p><strong>This concept applies perfectly to the act of giving in Japanese.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>In English, we use the word \u201cgive\u201d to describe the act of someone giving something to someone. It does not matter what direction that act of giving occurs.<\/p>\n<p>We can show this easily using a diagram similar to the one above:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1875\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/02-giving-different-directions.png\" alt=\"Giving in different directions\" width=\"1060\" height=\"380\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/02-giving-different-directions.png 1060w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/02-giving-different-directions-300x108.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/02-giving-different-directions-1024x367.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/02-giving-different-directions-768x275.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1060px) 100vw, 1060px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The direction of the giving does not matter \u2013 the word we use to describe that action is the same.<\/p>\n<p>In Japanese, the word we use is different. Let\u2019s take a look:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1876\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/03-agemasu-vs-kuremasu.png\" alt=\"Agemasu vs Kuremasu\" width=\"1060\" height=\"380\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/03-agemasu-vs-kuremasu.png 1060w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/03-agemasu-vs-kuremasu-300x108.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/03-agemasu-vs-kuremasu-1024x367.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/03-agemasu-vs-kuremasu-768x275.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1060px) 100vw, 1060px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Just like with the words \u201cgo\u201d and \u201ccome\u201d, Japanese has two different words to describe the same action depending on the perspective.<\/p>\n<p>In terms of the direction of the movement:<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Go\u00a0\u2248 <span class=\"ilRom\">agemasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Come\u00a0\u2248 <span class=\"ilRom\">kuremasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/p>\n<p>So, if you ever need to say that someone gave something to someone else, it should be very clear which word you should choose.<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the direction of the giving is away from you, use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<li>If the direction of the giving is towards you, use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>And, just like the word \u201cgo\u201d&#8230;<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the direction of the \u201cgiving\u201d is between two distant entities \u2013 neither towards you nor away from you \u2013 then we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>That\u2019s the main thing to remember. Now let\u2019s look at some examples so we can see how this works in practice.<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"give-examples\">Example sentences using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>Firstly, let\u2019s start with a sentence describing \u201cgoing\u201d and then morph it slightly to be an act of \u201cgiving\u201d instead:<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I will go to Y\u016bsuke&#8217;s house.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa y\u016bsuke no ie ni ikimasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306e \u3044\u3048 \u306b \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306e<ruby>\u5bb6<rt>\u3044\u3048<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I will give Y\u016bsuke a book.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa y\u016bsuke ni hon wo agemasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306b \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>Here these are in our <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">sentence structure<\/a> diagram:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1877\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1877\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1877 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke no ie ni ikimasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/04-watashi-wa-yusuke-no-ie-ni-ikimasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1877\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I go to Y\u016bsuke&#8217;s house.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1878\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1878\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1878 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo agemasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1878\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I give a book to Y\u016bsuke.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Note that:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>I, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;watashi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, am performing the act of giving, hence <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;watashi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> is the topic marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span>.<\/li>\n<li>The destination or end-point of each action is marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span>:\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"ilRom\">y\u016bsuke no ie ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306e<ruby>\u5bb6<rt>\u3044\u3048<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<\/span> = to Y\u016bsuke\u2019s house<\/li>\n<li><span class=\"ilRom\">y\u016bsuke ni<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b<\/span> = to Y\u016bsuke<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>The biggest difference is that in the \u201cgiving\u201d sentence, there is another element \u2013 <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;hon&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, a book. This is the thing the act of giving is done to, so it is the object of the sentence, and therefore marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n<p>We never have such an object in a sentence using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ikimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> because, well, you don\u2019t \u201cgo something\u201d like you might \u201cgive something\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>Overall, the sentences have a very similar structure, and they both describe the movement of something (ie. \u201cme\u201d or a book) away from the person speaking.<\/p>\n<p>Now let\u2019s look at an example using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6765<rt>\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>:<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">Y\u016bsuke comes to my house.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">y\u016bsuke wa watashi no ie ni kimasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306f \u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306e \u3044\u3048 \u306b \u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306f<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306e<ruby>\u5bb6<rt>\u3044\u3048<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u6765<rt>\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">Y\u016bsuke gives a book to me.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">y\u016bsuke wa watashi ni hon wo kuremasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306f \u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306b \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\">\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306f<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>Here these are in diagram form:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1904\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1904\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1904 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu.png\" alt=\"yusuke wa watashi no ie ni kimasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/06-yusuke-wa-watashi-no-ie-ni-kimasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1904\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Y\u016bsuke comes to my house.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1905\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1905\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1905 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu.png\" alt=\"yusuke wa watashi ni hon wo kuremasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1905\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Y\u016bsuke gives a book to me.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>If we put this side-by-side with our <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> example, you can see that they are basically the same:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1878\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1878\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1878 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo agemasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/05-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1878\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I give a book to Y\u016bsuke.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1905\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1905\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1905 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu.png\" alt=\"yusuke wa watashi ni hon wo kuremasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/07-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremasu-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1905\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Y\u016bsuke gives a book to me.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>All we have done, really, is swap <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;watashi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;y\u016bsuke&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u300d<\/span>, and, since that changes the direction of the movement to be towards us, we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> instead.<\/p>\n<p>So, in both cases, the structure is basically this:<\/p>\n<p><figure id=\"attachment_1881\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1881\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1881 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give.png\" alt=\"[topic] wa [destination] ni [object] wo agemasu\/kuremasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"582\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give-300x79.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give-1024x271.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give-768x203.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give-1536x406.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/08-topic-destination-object-give-2048x542.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1881\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">[Topic] gives [object] to [destination]<\/figcaption><\/figure>We just choose <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> or <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> depending on whether we are the originator of the giving, or the destination.<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"indirect-objects\">The non-existence of indirect objects<\/h3>\n<p>As a bit of a side note, English has these fun things called indirect objects that allow us to express the same exact idea in two different ways. I only mention it because Japanese <em>does not<\/em> have an equivalent expression, so this might save you from wondering if there is.<\/p>\n<p>Consider these sentences with perfectly equivalent meanings:<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">I will give a book to Y\u016bsuke.<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">I will give Y\u016bsuke a book.<\/p>\n<p>Now, the first example is almost identical to how Japanese treats these situations.<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Subject = I (because it\u2019s before the verb, &#8220;will give&#8221;)<\/li>\n<li>Object = a book (because it\u2019s after the verb)<\/li>\n<li>Destination = Y\u016bsuke (because the preposition \u201cto\u201d tells us so)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>The second sentence, however, puts \u201cY\u016bsuke\u201d in between the verb and \u201ca book\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>This is called an indirect object.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cA book\u201d is still the object &#8211; or more precisely, the direct object &#8211; since it is the thing being given, but we can insert a person in between the verb and the object as an indirect object to tell us that that person is the recipient. This also works with verbs like \u201csend\u201d (I sent my friend a book = to my friend), or even \u201cbuy\u201d (I bought my friend a book = for my friend).<\/p>\n<p>In Japanese, of course, the sentence always looks like this:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1903\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1903\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1903 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo agemasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"654\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-300x89.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1024x304.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-768x228.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-1536x457.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/09-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemasu-2048x609.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1903\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I give a book to Y\u016bsuke.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>The order of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;y\u016bsuke ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;hon wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u300d<\/span> doesn\u2019t really matter, so although we do have two options for this sentence\u2026<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I will give Y\u016bsuke a book.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa <strong><u>y\u016bsuke ni<\/u> <u>hon wo<\/u><\/strong> agemasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f <strong><u>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306b<\/u> <u>\u307b\u3093 \u3092<\/u><\/strong> \u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<strong><u>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b<\/u> <u><ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<\/u><\/strong>\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>&#8230;and&#8230;<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I will give Y\u016bsuke a book.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa <strong><u>hon wo<\/u> <u>y\u016bsuke ni<\/u><\/strong> agemasu.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f <strong><u>\u307b\u3093 \u3092<\/u> <u>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306b<\/u><\/strong> \u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<strong><u><ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<\/u> <u>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b<\/u><\/strong>\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>\u2026the rules are no different to any other sentence.<\/p>\n<p>Particles tell us everything we need to know, so as long as we attach the right ones, we don\u2019t really have to worry too much about word order.<\/p>\n<p>This is one example of why Japanese is so simple. English learners have to use word order to figure out if something is an object or an indirect object, and if they get it backwards, they end up giving people way instead of books. In Japanese, we just need to know which particle does what and that\u2019s it.<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"less-obvious-cases\">Determining which direction applies in less-obvious cases<\/h3>\n<p>Most of the time, it is fairly easy to determine if the direction of the movement of an object is towards us or away from us, but there are a few potentially confusing situations we should clarify.<\/p>\n<p>Firstly, as mentioned earlier, if you are talking about an act of giving that is directed away from yourself, or between two third parties, use the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n<p>This is the same as if you were talking about someone going away from you, or between two distant locations (point A to point B) \u2013 you would use the word \u201cgo\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>You would only use the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> when the direction of the movement is towards you, just as you would only use the word \u201ccome\u201d if the direction of the movement is towards you. This diagram sums it up:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1883\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/10-giving-triangle.png\" alt=\"Giving triangle using agemasu and kuremasu\" width=\"835\" height=\"584\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/10-giving-triangle.png 835w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/10-giving-triangle-300x210.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/10-giving-triangle-768x537.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 835px) 100vw, 835px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Secondly, the use of the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is not limited to discussion about yourself personally \u2013 it also applies to people in your group.<\/p>\n<p>For example, if I am talking to Y\u016bsuke about something that Asami gave to Y\u016bsuke, I should use the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, even though I myself am not the recipient. I think we need another diagram:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1884\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/11-giving-to-associate.png\" alt=\"Using kuremasu with an associate\" width=\"940\" height=\"470\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/11-giving-to-associate.png 940w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/11-giving-to-associate-300x150.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/11-giving-to-associate-768x384.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 940px) 100vw, 940px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The reason for this is because, since Y\u016bsuke and I are in the conversation together, the direction of the giving is still towards me, relatively. Yes, it\u2019s primarily towards Y\u016bsuke, but because Y\u016bsuke and I are together at the time of this conversation, from my perspective, the gift has moved in my direction.<\/p>\n<p>Again, this is (in most cases) the same as the normal use of the word\u00a0<span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6765<rt>\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>\u00a0(come). If instead of a book, Asami herself moved towards Y\u016bsuke, and I was with Y\u016bsuke discussing this, I would describe this action using the word \u201ccome\u201d, not \u201cgo\u201d.<\/p>\n<h2 id=\"receive\">How to say \u201creceive\u201d in Japanese &#8211; Moraimasu<\/h2>\n<p>The words for giving and receiving are usually introduced together, and they are, of course, very much related, but we need to be clear about something.<\/p>\n<p><strong>The concept of \u201creceiving\u201d has absolutely no impact on your choice of the word for \u201cgiving\u201d.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>That\u2019s why we haven\u2019t mentioned it yet.<\/p>\n<p>If you want to say that one person gave something to another person, you use one of the words that means \u201cgive\u201d, and we now know how to choose the appropriate one.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Receiving is a different action.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>Yes, the event of one person passing an object to another person is the same regardless of what word we use to describe it, but that\u2019s irrelevant.<\/p>\n<p>Why?<\/p>\n<p>Because <strong>the person who performs the action is different<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>This may seem very obvious, but when you GIVE something to someone, YOU give it, and THEY receive it. Those are two separate actions.<\/p>\n<p>Consider this event:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1885\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12-pen-going-to-taro.png\" alt=\"Pen going from Ken to Taro\" width=\"708\" height=\"380\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12-pen-going-to-taro.png 708w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12-pen-going-to-taro-300x161.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 708px) 100vw, 708px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>We can describe this one of two ways:<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\"><strong>Ken gives<\/strong> Tar\u014d a pen.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\"><strong>ken wa<\/strong> tar\u014d ni pen wo <strong>agemasu<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\"><strong>\u3051\u3093 \u306f<\/strong> \u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306b \u30da\u30f3 \u3092 <strong>\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/strong>\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><strong>\u3051\u3093\u306f<\/strong>\u305f\u308d\u3046\u306b\u30da\u30f3\u3092<strong>\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/strong>\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\"><strong>Tar\u014d receives<\/strong> a pen from Ken.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\"><strong>tar\u014d wa<\/strong> ken ni pen wo <strong>moraimasu<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\"><strong>\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f<\/strong> \u3051\u3093 \u306b \u30da\u30f3 \u3092 <strong>\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/strong>\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><strong>\u305f\u308d\u3046\u306f<\/strong>\u3051\u3093\u306b\u30da\u30f3\u3092<strong>\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/strong>\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>The topic of these sentences is different. One is talking about an action that Ken does, the other is talking about an action that Taro does. They are different actions, even if both refer to the same actual event.<\/p>\n<p>Remembering this should help us a lot in choosing the appropriate particles.<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"moraimasu-particles\">Which particles to use with &#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/h3>\n<p>For the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, the person performing the act of receiving is the topic. Here\u2019s a basic example in the past tense:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1886\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1886\" style=\"width: 2400px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1886 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/13-watashi-wa-hon-wo-moraimashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa hon wo moraimashita\" width=\"2400\" height=\"426\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1886\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I received a book<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>If we want to say who the book was received from, then we need to include the origin. One way to do this is to use the basic origin element that uses the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>:<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I received a book <strong>from Y\u016bsuke<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa <strong>y\u016bsuke kara<\/strong> hon wo moraimashita.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f <strong>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u304b\u3089<\/strong> \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<strong>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u304b\u3089<\/strong><ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>Here&#8217;s this sentence in diagram form:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1887\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1887\" style=\"width: 2400px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1887 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/14-watashi-wa-yusuke-kara-hon-wo-moraimashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke kara hon wo moraimashita\" width=\"2400\" height=\"426\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1887\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I received a book from Y\u016bsuke<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>However, we can also (and generally should) use the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> instead of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>. This probably seems like a strange choice, but there is a very good reason for it.<\/p>\n<p>As we have already seen, one of the uses of the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is to define the <em><strong>destination<\/strong> <\/em>of an action involving movement. Here, however, it is describing the <em><strong>origin<\/strong><\/em> of an action involving movement \u2013 the exact opposite.<\/p>\n<p>The reason for this is <strong>because the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is <em>passive<\/em> in nature<\/strong>. This is unlike most other regular verbs, which are <em>active<\/em> in nature.<\/p>\n<p>A verb that is passive describes an action from the perspective of a person that didn\u2019t actually have to do anything themselves. Instead, they had something done to them, and their role in the action was passive. Rather than <em>do<\/em> the action, they <em>undergo<\/em> it.<\/p>\n<p>In the case of receiving something, a person can literally do nothing in the process of receiving. The person that actually moved their body to make something happen is someone else \u2013 the person that gave them something. So, Taro can just kick back while Ken does all the work:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1915\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12a-Taro-receiving-a-pen.png\" alt=\"Taro receiving a pen from Ken\" width=\"708\" height=\"380\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12a-Taro-receiving-a-pen.png 708w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/12a-Taro-receiving-a-pen-300x161.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 708px) 100vw, 708px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Most regular verbs are active by nature, but they usually also have a passive form. This is the same in both English and Japanese.\u00a0For example, the passive form of \u201cto see\u201d is, \u201cto be seen\u201d. In Japanese, too, the passive form of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;mimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>(meaning \u201csee\u201d) is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;miraremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3089\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> (\u201cto be seen\u201d). This is not really a separate word, but just the passive form of a verb that is usually active. Most passive verbs are derived from active verbs in a similar way.<\/p>\n<p>In the case of\u00a0<span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, it could be argued that it, too, is technically an active verb, but its meaning is predominantly passive.<\/p>\n<p>More importantly, the way we use it is consistent with passive verbs, particularly when it comes to choosing a particle.<\/p>\n<p>The use of a passive verb effectively causes the meaning of the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> to flip, so<strong>\u00a0instead of describing the destination, it describes the origin.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>So, taking this into account, we can rewrite this sentence like this:<\/p>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">I received a book <strong>from Y\u016bsuke<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa <strong>y\u016bsuke ni<\/strong> hon wo moraimashita.<\/p>\n<p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f <strong>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051 \u306b<\/strong> \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<strong>\u3086\u3046\u3059\u3051\u306b<\/strong><ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<p>And we can represent this in our diagram as follows:<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1888\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1888\" style=\"width: 2400px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1888 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/15-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-moraimashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo moraimashita\" width=\"2400\" height=\"426\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1888\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I received a book from Y\u016bsuke.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>Now, let\u2019s look again at the examples from earlier using the words <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> (except this time in the past tense).<\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1889\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1889\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1889 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo agemashita\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/16-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-agemashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1889\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">I gave Y\u016bsuke a book.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_1894\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-1894\" style=\"width: 2200px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-1894 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita.png\" alt=\"yusuke wa watashi ni hon wo kuremashita\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/17-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kuremashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-1894\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Y\u016bsuke gave me a book.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>As you can see, the topic of these sentences is the GIVER, while the topic of our sentence with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is the RECEIVER.<\/p>\n<p>Meanwhile, the role of the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> is also flipped. It tells us the destination of the object being given when using one of the two active \u201cgive\u201d words, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, but it defines the origin of the object being received when using the passive word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n<p>Lastly, as with the &#8220;giving&#8221; sentences, the order of the &#8216;Other Information&#8217; &#8211; the origin and the object &#8211; does not really affect the meaning, so more generally, the structure looks like this:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1909\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive.png\" alt=\"[topic] wa [origin] ni [object] wo moraimasu\" width=\"2200\" height=\"582\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive-300x79.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive-1024x271.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive-768x203.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive-1536x406.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/18-topic-origin-object-receive-2048x542.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><\/p>\n<div class=\"rw-sidebar\">\n<h3 id=\"alt-approach-to-ni\">An alternative way to think about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>Rather than thinking of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> as the particle for marking a destination or origin, we could think about it as marking a counterparty. That is:<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>When talking about giving and receiving, the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> defines the counterparty.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>The counterparty is, of course, the receiver when the verb describes giving (<span class=\"ilRom\">agemasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/span> or <span class=\"ilRom\">kuremasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059<\/span>), and the giver when the verb describes receiving (<span class=\"ilRom\">moraimasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/span>).<\/p>\n<p>This is simpler in some ways, but I have chosen the destination\/origin description because these terms have a much more obvious sense of direction. They also align well with other situations where there is a verb involving movement, such as &#8220;go&#8221; and &#8220;come&#8221;, so it reduces the number of definitions for <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> that we need to remember.<\/p>\n<p>Of course, if &#8220;counterparty&#8221; makes more sense to you, use that!<\/p>\n<\/div>\n<h2 id=\"super-polite\">Bonus: Super-polite verbs for giving and receiving<\/h2>\n<p>The basic, polite forms of these three verbs are the ones we have used thus far: <span class=\"ilRom\">agemasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/span>, <span class=\"ilRom\">kuremasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">moraimasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/span>.<\/p>\n<p>The informal\/dictionary forms of these verbs are very similar: <span class=\"ilRom\">ageru<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u308b<\/span>, <span class=\"ilRom\">kureru<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u308b<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">morau<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3082\u3089\u3046<\/span>. These are simply a different conjugation of the same three verbs.<\/p>\n<p>If, however, we go up another level from basic politeness to what we might call the \u201csuper-polite\u201d form, the words change completely (well, two of them do anyway).<\/p>\n<p>And, since the acts of giving and receiving are a fairly important part of Japanese etiquette and culture, you are likely to hear these more frequently than many other super-polite terms.<\/p>\n<p>Here is the present\/future tense of all three politeness levels together:<\/p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>English<\/th>\n<th>Informal<\/th>\n<th>Polite<\/th>\n<th>Super-polite<\/th>\n<\/tr>\n<\/thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Give (away from yourself)<\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">ageru<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u308b<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">agemasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">sashiagemasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3055\u3057\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Give (towards yourself)<\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">kureru<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u308b<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">kuremasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">kudasaimasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Receive<\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">morau<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3082\u3089\u3046<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">moraimasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<td><span class=\"ilRom\">itadakimasu<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3044\u305f\u3060\u304d\u307e\u3059<\/span><\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n<p>You might recognise two of these in particular:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>The word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kudasai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044\u300d<\/span>, meaning &#8220;please&#8221;, is from <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kudasaimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>. So, when you say something like, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;matte kudasai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5f85<rt>\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3063\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044\u300d<\/span> (please wait), you are sort of saying, \u201cgive to me by waiting\u201d.<\/li>\n<li>The word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;itadakimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u305f\u3060\u304d\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is what Japanese people say before they eat. They are effectively saying, \u201cI will receive (this food)\u201d.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>Anywho, we can use these verbs in a sentence by simply substituting them for their less polite equivalents:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1910 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo sashiagemashita\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/19-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-sashiagemashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1911 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita.png\" alt=\"yusuke wa watashi ni hon wo kudasaimashita\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/20-yusuke-wa-watashi-ni-hon-wo-kudasaimashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1912 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita.png\" alt=\"watashi wa yusuke ni hon wo itadakimashita\" width=\"2200\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita.png 2200w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/21-watashi-wa-yusuke-ni-hon-wo-itadakimashita-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2200px) 100vw, 2200px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Of course, given that you are describing giving\/receiving something to\/from someone &#8220;above&#8221; you, you would generally substitute &#8220;Y\u016bsuke&#8221; for a more polite name or title, but that&#8217;s a whole other discussion for another day.<\/p>\n<h2 id=\"takeaways\">Key Takeaways<\/h2>\n<p>Describing giving and receiving in Japanese is quite simple if we internalise a few basic rules.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Giving<\/strong><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>There are two words for &#8220;give&#8221;: <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<li><strong><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;Agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/strong> should be used when the direction of the giving <strong>is away from you, or between two third-parties<\/strong>. It has the same directionality as the word \u201cgo\u201d.<\/li>\n<li><strong><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;Kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/strong> should be used when the direction of the giving is <strong>towards you<\/strong>, including situations where you are simply closer to the recipient than the giver. It has the same directionality as the word \u201ccome\u201d.<\/li>\n<li>The giver is the topic\/subject of the sentence. That is, the person who does the giving is the person performing the action described by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<li>The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> defines the destination of the giving \u2013 that is, the recipient.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><strong>Receiving<\/strong><\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>There is one word for &#8220;receive&#8221;: <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<li>The receiver is the topic\/subject of the sentence. That is, the person who does the receiving is the person performing the action described by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>. This is the opposite of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;agemasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3042\u3052\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304f\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d.<\/span><\/li>\n<li>Since the verb <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;moraimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3082\u3089\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> is passive in nature, the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ni&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306b\u300d<\/span> defines the origin of the thing being given.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>Basically, this:<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1893\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/Giving-and-receiving-in-Japanese.png\" alt=\"Giving and receiving in Japanese\" width=\"1280\" height=\"720\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/Giving-and-receiving-in-Japanese.png 1280w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/Giving-and-receiving-in-Japanese-300x169.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/Giving-and-receiving-in-Japanese-1024x576.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/01\/Giving-and-receiving-in-Japanese-768x432.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px\" \/><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The words used to describe the acts of giving and receiving in Japanese can be quite confusing, but they needn\u2019t be. In a nutshell, there are two words that mean \u201cto give\u201d: agemasu kuremasu And another word that means \u201cto receive\u201d: moraimasu What most often confuses people is the fact that there are three words [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":4,"featured_media":1893,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[4],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-1863","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-grammar","post-wrapper","thrv_wrapper"],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v25.9 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>Giving and Receiving in Japanese - Agemasu, Kuremasu, Moraimasu - 80\/20 Japanese<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1